final_thought: The river used to sing back to us. Now it just roars.
last_days_scenario: Mei sits by the muddy Yangtze at dawn, holding her father's fishing
  whistle. The container ships start their engines at 5 AM now - earlier each year.
  She remembers when you could hear individual fish jumping, when her grandmother
  could predict weather by river-sound. The water is brown with industrial runoff.
  Her dialect has no words for the new chemical smells. The relocation notice from
  the Three Gorges Corporation sits unopened on her kitchen table - they're building
  another shipping channel through Shizhou Village. She puts the whistle to her lips
  but doesn't blow - what's the point? The river can't hear her anymore.
